# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: boilover
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] Manual fire suppression includes the use of a fire blanket, fire extinguisher, or a standpipe system.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] A fire blanket is a sheet of fire retardant material that is designed to be placed over a fire to smother it out.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] Small fire blankets are meant for inception stage fires.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] They are normally made of fiberglass or Kevlar.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] Larger ones can be found in laboratories and factories, and are designed to be wrapped around a person whose clothes have caught fire.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers are devices that contain and discharge a substance that extinguishes or puts out a fire.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] These handheld devices come in a huge range of sizes, but the most common are portable fire extinguishers, typically weighing up to 15 kg in total.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] These can be easily handled and operated by one person and placement can either be wall-mounted, on a fire extinguisher trolley or housed inside a cabinet.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers are one of the most common manual fire suppression devices and are required in all commercial buildings and vehicles.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers can be used with little to no training and are meant for small incipient stage fires.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] The most common extinguisher is the ABC extinguisher and are found in most offices and homes.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] It can be used on normal fires, liquid fires, and electrical fires.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] There are also special extinguishers for kitchen fires and for use on burning metals, those being Class K and Class D respectively.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] Standpipes are installed in most large, multistory buildings.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] There are two types of standpipes: dry and wet.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] Most standpipes are dry systems and cannot be used by the public.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] Dry systems require a fire engine to pump water into the system.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] Most dry systems do not have pre-connected hoses and require firefighters to bring in the hose.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] In wet systems, there is always water in the pipes and they can be used by anyone.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] Wet systems will have hoses so building occupants can try and extinguish fires.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] Wet systems are becoming less common with the increase in number of sprinkler systems being installed.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] In some systems, firefighters have the option of pumping a Fire Department Connection (FDC) which will increase the water pressure at a standpipe in the event of a fire pump failure or loss of pressure.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] Typically, these systems pressurize the sprinkler system or the standpipe but not both at the same time.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] Automatic control means are any form of suppression that requires no human intervention these can include a fire sprinkler system, a gaseous clean agent, or automatic foam suppression system.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] Most automatic suppression systems would be found in large commercial kitchens or other high-risk areas.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] Fire sprinkler systems are installed in all types of buildings, commercial and residential.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] They are usually located at ceiling level and are connected to a reliable water source, most commonly municipal water supply.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] A typical automatic sprinkler system operates when heat at the site of a fire causes a fusible link or glass component in the sprinkler head to fail, thereby releasing the water from the sprinkler head.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] This means that only the sprinkler heads at the fire location actuate – not all the sprinklers on a floor or in a building.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] However, certain systems, such as deluge systems, do spray water from all heads in the same zone upon actuation.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] Sprinkler systems help to reduce the growth of a fire, thereby increasing life safety and limiting structural damage.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] Gaseous clean agents are installed to result in less fire and water damage than sprinklers, such as in computer rooms.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] The system works by flooding an area with a gas which interferes with the fire tetrahedron.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] These systems are often found in areas where people are not going to be present when the system is activated such as datacenters, cooling systems, and other industrial applications.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] Activating a gaseous clean agent system when people are present can cause injury or death, and are usually equipped with an audible notification system to warn any potential occupants to evacuate the area.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] Automatic foam suppression systems come in three main forms low expansion, medium expansion, and high expansion.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] Low expansion foam expands less than 20 times its original size.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] These systems can be installed in a variety of places but are commonly found in places where hydrocarbons are stored.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] Low expansion foam systems when using film forming work by making a blanket of foam over the burning liquid to both cool it down and suppress the vapors.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] Medium expansion foam expands between 20 and 200 times its original size.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] These can be installed in outdoor settings like transfer stations or for use in open pits.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] Medium foam is used outdoors because it is denser than high expansion and will not blow away as easily.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] It works by covering what is on fire in a thick blanket of foam to smother it and suppress vapors.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] High expansion foam expands between 200 and 1000 times its original size.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] These systems are commonly installed in large volume areas like airplane hangars, mine shafts, and ship holds.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] These systems are normally installed inside and make a very light foam.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] They extinguish the fire by rapid smothering and cooling.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] Its rapid rate of expansion enables it to fill large areas with foam rapidly.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] When used on LNG tanks they provide an added insulation layer that helps reduce the vapor rate.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] Nozzles that are powered by electrical energy that is generated and supplied by fire detection and control devices and are typically closed.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] ILDFA uses a dual approach, combining a water-based fire suppression system in conjunction with a hollow, perforated flooring system to drain and remove spilled flammable liquid.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] This approach reduces the risk of pool fires inside infrastructure by diverting any leaked fuel away from potential ignition sources or by extinguishing any flammable liquid fire by depriving it of oxygen once it is removed.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] Fire detection works using smoke or heat sensors.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] These systems are very effective tool at alerting people in the immediate vicinity of where the fire is detected but building regulations require an integrated fire detection system.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] These system not only alerts people throughout the building by triggering the fire alarm but it can also summon emergency services.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] There are two types of systems available – addressable and conventional.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] Addressable systems monitor the specific location of each device (e.g. smoke detector, call point or sounder).
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] It means in the event of a fire or other emergency you know exactly where the problem is.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] This saves precious time and helps the emergency services prevent the loss of life and serious damage.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] Conventional systems can only determine the problem is in a general area and thus are more suited for small sites.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] When the fire detection system is activated it can also send an alert to the local fire department, broadcast a prerecorded warning message and unlock the buildings access control system.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] Hypoxic air fire prevention systems, also known as oxygen reduction systems are new automatic fire prevention systems that permanently reduce the oxygen concentration inside the protected volumes so that ignition or fire spreading cannot occur.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] Unlike traditional fire suppression systems that usually extinguish fire after it is detected, hypoxic air is able to prevent fires.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] At lower altitudes hypoxic air is safe to breathe for healthy individuals.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] All AFP systems are required to be installed and maintained in accordance with strict guidelines in order to maintain compliance with the local building code and the fire code.
[src:boilover/active-fire-protection] AFP works alongside modern architectural designs and construction materials and fire safety education to prevent, retard, and suppress structural fires.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] The **American Petroleum Institute** (**API**) is the largest U.S. trade association for the oil and natural gas industry.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] It claims to represent nearly 600 corporations involved in production, refinement, distribution, and many other aspects of the petroleum industry.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] It has advanced climate change denial and blocking of climate legislation to defend the interests of its constituent organizations.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] The association describes its mission as "to promote safety across the industry globally and influence public policy in support of a strong, viable U.S. oil and natural gas industry".
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] API's chief functions on behalf of the industry include advocacy, negotiation and lobbying with governmental, legal, and regulatory agencies; research into economic, toxicological, and environmental effects; establishment and certification of industry standards; and education outreach.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] API both funds and conducts research related to many aspects of the petroleum industry.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] Although some oil was produced commercially before 1859 as a byproduct from salt brine wells, the American oil industry started on a major scale with the discovery of oil at the Drake Well in western Pennsylvania in 1859.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] The American Petroleum Institute was founded on March 20, 1919, and based in New York City.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] In 1959, at a symposium organized by the American Petroleum Institute and the Columbia Graduate School of Business for the centennial of the American oil industry, the physicist Edward Teller warned then of the danger of global climate change.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] Edward Teller explained that carbon dioxide "in the atmosphere causes a greenhouse effect" and that burning more fossil fuels could "melt the icecap and submerge New York".
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] In 1969, the API decided to move its offices to Washington, DC.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] API Standards Committees are made up of subcommittees and task groups that works and maintain these standards.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] API also defines the industry standard for the energy conservation of motor oil.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] As of 2020 **API SP** is the latest specification.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] SP specifies more stringent engine oil performance requirements for spark-ignited internal combustion engines.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] These include a chain wear test and a test for very low-viscosity engine oils.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] The standards also include a test designed to protect against a phenomenon experienced by some gasoline engines known as Low-Speed Pre-Ignition (LSPI).
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] API also defines and drafts standards for measurement for manufactured products.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] Crude Oil Data Exchange (CODE) is the electronic business standard as of 1978.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] API RP 500 and RP 505 classify the locations for electrical equipment in hazardous areas.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] In addition to training industry workers and conducting seminars, workshops, and conferences on public policy, API develops and distributes materials and curricula for schoolchildren and educators.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] The association also maintains a website, *Classroom Energ*y.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] API spent more than $3 million annually during the period 2005 to 2009 on lobbying.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] As of 2009, according to API’s quarterly “Lobbying Report” submitted to the U.S.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] Senate, the organization had 16 lobbyists lobbying Congress.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] The American Petroleum Institute also lobbied the State Department every quarter in 2009.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] In three of four quarters, the group listed “legislative efforts concerning oil sands” as one of the areas it was focusing on in its lobbying, and in the final quarter, it listed “Canadian Oil Sands.” Among API’s members are ExxonMobil, which has invested in Canadian oil sands.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] API lobbies and organizes its member employees' attendance at public events to communicate the industry's position on issues.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] A leaked summer 2009 memo from then API President Jack Gerard asked its member companies to urge their employees to participate in planned protests (designed to appear independently organized) against the cap-and-trade legislation the House passed that same summer.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] "The objective of these rallies is to put a human face on the impacts of unsound energy policy and to aim a loud message at [20 different] states," including Florida, Georgia, and Pennsylvania.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] Gerard went on to assure recipients of the memo that API will cover all organizational costs and handling of logistics.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] In response to the memo, an API spokesman told media that participants will be there (at protests) because of their own concerns, and that API is just helping them assemble.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] To help fight climate control legislation that has been approved by the U.S.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] House, API supports the Energy Citizens group, which is holding public events.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] API encouraged energy company employees to attend one of its first Energy Citizen events held in Houston in August 2009, but turned away Texas residents who were not employed by the energy industry.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] *Fast Company* reported that some attendees had no idea of the purpose of the event.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] In December 2009, *Mother Jones* magazine said API and Energy Citizens were promulgating climate disinformation.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] In January 2012, the American Petroleum Institute launched the voter education campaign – Vote 4 Energy.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] The campaign says that increased domestic energy production can create jobs, increase government revenue, and provide U.S. energy security.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] The Vote 4 Energy campaign does not promote any specific candidate or party, but rather provides voters with energy information to equip them to evaluate candidates on the federal and local levels and make decisions in favor of domestic energy on Election Day.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] The main components of the Vote 4 Energy campaign include the website – Vote4Energy.org – and social media communities, along with a series of advertisements and events around the country.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] The Vote 4 Energy campaign was criticized for presenting misleading arguments about the relationship between oil production and jobs whilst ignoring the potentially catastrophic consequences of increased fossil fuel consumption on the Earth's climate.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] The API successfully pushed for an end to a ban on American oil exports on the grounds that the ban increased demand for Russian and Iranian oil, thereby benefiting the unfriendly regimes in these countries.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] Critics noted that many of its member companies continued to maintain ongoing business in these countries whilst the lobbying campaign was in progress, leading to accusations of hypocrisy.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] Furthermore, the API's campaigns have been criticized for advocating policies that are likely to exacerbate global warming and its associated problems.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] The API has repeatedly funded conservative groups that deny the reality of anthropogenic global warming in spite of the overwhelming scientific consensus that it presents a serious problem for the planet.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] It has many front groups, including the NH Energy Forum that in August 2011 hosted a New Hampshire event for Republican presidential candidate Rick Perry.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] In March 2022, the Climate Committee of the API reportedly approved a draft proposal urging Congress to pass a carbon tax on fossil fuels.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] The draft proposal is subject to further approval by the API Executive Committee.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] The proposal calls for gasoline wholesalers, power plants and others to pay a tax of $35 to $50 per ton of carbon dioxide generated by the fossil fuel they sell or use.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] The proposal drew criticism amid coincident high prices at the pump and elsewhere.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] In June 2021, in a sting operation carried out by *Unearthed*, senior ExxonMobil lobbyist Keith McCoy revealed that the company was 'for a carbon tax' because 'it gives us a talking point'.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] In reality, McCoy stated, a carbon tax 'is not gonna happen'.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] In February 2015, it was revealed that climate denier Willie Soon had been paid by several fossil fuel interest groups.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] Over the course of 14 years, he had received a total of $1.25m from Exxon Mobil, Southern Company, the American Petroleum Institute (API) and a foundation run by the libertarian Koch brothers, the documents obtained by Greenpeace show.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] The scientist described his studies to fossil fuel executives as "deliverables", and permitted anonymous pre-publication reviews.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] Soon advanced the widely discredited theory that changes in solar activity are to blame for climate change, and called into question the severity and extent of climate change in all his studies, never revealing his backers.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] Every Tuesday (unless Monday is a holiday) at 4:30 PM the API releases a report on US inventories of crude oil, gasoline and distillates, to paid subscribers.
[src:boilover/american-petroleum-institute] As this information predates the report on the same inventory levels by the Energy Information Administration (EIA), it gives investors an early look at the information that may be coming from the EIA, although there is frequently some disparity between the two sets of figures.
[src:boilover/amoco] In 1925, Standard Oil of Indiana absorbed the **American Oil Company**, founded in Baltimore in 1910, and incorporated in 1922, by Louis Blaustein and his son Jacob.
[src:boilover/amoco] The combined corporation operated or licensed gas stations under both the *Standard* name and the *American* or *Amoco* name (the latter from *American Oil Company*) and its logo using these names became a red, white and blue oval with a torch in the center.
[src:boilover/amoco] By the mid-twentieth century it was ranked the largest oil company in the United States.
[src:boilover/amoco] In 1985, it changed its corporate name to Amoco.
[src:boilover/amoco] The firm's innovations included two essential parts of the modern industry, the gasoline tanker truck and the drive-through filling station.
[src:boilover/amoco] Its "Amoco Super-Premium" lead-free gasoline was marketed decades before environmental concerns led to the eventual phasing out of leaded gasoline throughout the United States.
[src:boilover/amoco] Amoco's headquarters were located in the Amoco Building (also called the Standard Oil Building, and nicknamed "Big Stan", now the Aon Center) in Chicago, Illinois.
[src:boilover/amoco] Amoco merged with BP in December 1998 to form BP Amoco, which was renamed BP in 2001.
[src:boilover/amoco] The Amoco name was branded at the gas pump for the highest 93 octane blends.
[src:boilover/amoco] The *Deepwater Horizon* oil spill of 2010 tarnished the BP brand in the US, resulting in the re-consideration of US branding.
[src:boilover/amoco] In October 2017, BP announced re-introduction of the Amoco branded stations to selected US markets.
[src:boilover/amoco] As of 2023, there were over 600 new Amoco stations in the eastern and midwestern United States.
[src:boilover/amoco] Standard Oil of Indiana was formed in 1889 by John D.
[src:boilover/amoco] Rockefeller as part of the Standard Oil Trust.
[src:boilover/amoco] The company's operations centered around the Whiting Refinery situated on Lake Michigan, and first operational in 1890.
[src:boilover/amoco] In 1910, with the increased usage of the automobile, Indiana Standard decided to specialize in providing gasoline to consumers.
[src:boilover/amoco] In 1911, the year it became independent from the Standard Oil trust, the company sold 88% of the gasoline and kerosene sold in the Midwest.
[src:boilover/amoco] In 1912, it opened its first gas service station in Minneapolis, Minnesota.
[src:boilover/amoco] When the Standard Oil Trust was broken up in 1911, Indiana Standard was assigned marketing territory covering most of the Midwestern United States, including Indiana, Michigan, Illinois, Wisconsin, Minnesota, North Dakota, South Dakota, Iowa, Kansas, and Missouri.
[src:boilover/amoco] It had the exclusive rights to use the Standard name in the region.
[src:boilover/amoco] Soon after, Indiana Standard scientist William Burton pioneered a new way to process crude oil, called thermal cracking, which allowed the industry to produce more oil.
[src:boilover/amoco] The company licensed the process to 14 companies between 1914 and 1919, including former parent company Standard Oil of New Jersey.
[src:boilover/amoco] The company opened its Casper refinery in 1914.
[src:boilover/amoco] In 1918, Indiana Standard named Colonel Robert W.
[src:boilover/amoco] Under Stewart, it began investing in other oil companies outside its Standard marketing territory, beginning with the purchase of the Dixie Oil Company of Louisiana in 1919 and a one-third interest in Midwest Refining in 1920.
[src:boilover/amoco] By June 1921, Standard Oil owned 85% of Midwest's stock.
[src:boilover/amoco] By 1922, the company also had facilities in Sugar Creek, Missouri; Wood River, Illinois; and Greybull, and Laramie in Wyoming.
[src:boilover/amoco] The Casper facility was the largest volume gasoline refinery in the world by this time, turning 1.35 million barrels of crude oil per month into 615,000 barrels of gasoline.
[src:boilover/amoco] In the 1920s and 1930s, Indiana Standard opened up dozens more refining and oil-drilling facilities.
[src:boilover/amoco] Combined with a new oil-refining process, Indiana Standard created its exploration and production business, Stanolind, in 1931.
[src:boilover/amoco] In the following years, a period of intense exploration and search for oil-rich fields ensued; the company drilled over 1,000 wells in 1937 alone.
[src:boilover/amoco] After working for Standard Oil, Blaustein eventually saved enough capital to found his own oil company with his son in 1910.
[src:boilover/amoco] They called it the American Oil Company (AMOCO).
[src:boilover/amoco] Blaustein incorporated his business in 1922.
[src:boilover/amoco] In 1923, the Blausteins sold a half interest in American Oil to the Pan American Petroleum and Transport Company in exchange for a guaranteed supply of oil.
[src:boilover/amoco] Before this deal, Amoco was forced to depend on Standard Oil of New Jersey, a competitor, for its supplies.
[src:boilover/amoco] Standard Oil of Indiana acquired Pan American in 1925, beginning John D.
[src:boilover/amoco] Rockefeller's association with the Amoco name.
[src:boilover/amoco] In the wake of the infamous Teapot Dome scandal, it was discovered that Harry Sinclair, Robert Stewart, Albert Fall, and others, had been laundering money through a shell company called Continental Trading Company and using the funds to buy more than $3 million in liberty bonds during World War I.
[src:boilover/amoco] Though Stewart was never charged with a crime, John D.
[src:boilover/amoco] Rockefeller Jr. demanded his resignation.
[src:boilover/amoco] After a lengthy proxy fight between the two, Stewart was eventually ousted in March 1929.
[src:boilover/amoco] In 1925 Indiana Standard made a $36.7 million stake in the Pan American Petroleum and Transport Company gave the company interest in the American Oil Company, which marketed half of PAT's oil in the United States.
[src:boilover/amoco] Indiana Standard raised its stake in PAT to 81 percent by 1929.
[src:boilover/amoco] The two companies officially merged in 1954.
[src:boilover/amoco] In 1930, Standard completed its acquisition of Sinclair Pipeline and also acquired the remaining half of Sinclair Crude Oil Purchasing Company.
[src:boilover/amoco] The two companies were renamed to Stanolind Pipeline Company and Stanolind Crude Oil Purchasing Company.
[src:boilover/amoco] The pipeline company headquarters were located in the Philcade building in Tulsa, Oklahoma.
[src:boilover/amoco] In 1950, all of the corporation's pipeline activities were merged into a single entity, which was named Service Pipeline Company.
[src:boilover/amoco] By 1964, the company operated 14,500 miles of pipelines located in the central part of the country.
[src:boilover/amoco] It gathered crude oil from 34,300 wells and carried it to 59 refineries, delivering 900,000 to 950,000 barrels a day.
[src:boilover/amoco] While most oil companies were switching to leaded gasolines en masse during the mid-to-late 1920s, American Oil chose to continue marketing its premium-grade "Amoco-Gas" (later Amoco Super-Premium) as a lead-free gasoline by using aromatics rather than tetraethyllead to increase octane levels.
[src:boilover/amoco] This was decades before the environmental movement of the early 1970s that led to more stringent auto-emission controls, which ultimately mandated the universal phase out of leaded gasoline.
[src:boilover/amoco] The "Amoco" lead-free gasoline was sold at American's stations in the eastern and southern U.S. alongside American Regular gasoline, which was a leaded fuel.
[src:boilover/amoco] By 1970, lead-free Amoco was introduced in the Indiana Standard marketing area in 1970.
[src:boilover/amoco] The Red Crown Regular and White Crown Premium (later Gold Crown Super Premium) gasolines marketed by parent company Standard Oil (Indiana) in its prime marketing area in the Midwest before 1961, also contained lead.
[src:boilover/amoco] By 1978, Amoco had phased out premium lead gas.
[src:boilover/amoco] In November 1986, amid pressures from the EPA to cut down on the usage of lead in gasoline, Amoco became the first major oil company to say it would quit all retail sales of leaded gasoline.
[src:boilover/amoco] In its place, Amoco began selling a mid-grade 89 octane unleaded gasoline (the same number as its leaded regular gasoline), along with its unleaded regular and unleaded premium offerings.
[src:boilover/amoco] World War II followed this period of exploration; Indiana Standard participated in the war effort, discovering new means of refinement and even a way of producing TNT more quickly and easily.
[src:boilover/amoco] In addition, Indiana Standard significantly contributed to the aviation and land gasoline needed for the Allied armies.
[src:boilover/amoco] Also, during the war Indiana Standard created its chemical division, formed from the merger of the Pan American Chemicals Company and the Indoil Chemical Company.
[src:boilover/amoco] In the late 1940s, after World War II, Indiana Standard returned to focusing on domestic oil refinement and advancement.
[src:boilover/amoco] In 1947, Indiana Standard was the first company to drill off-shore, in the Gulf of Mexico, and in 1948, Stanolind Oil invented Hydrafrac, a hydraulic well fracturing process that increased oil production worldwide.
[src:boilover/amoco] Initially the Hydrafrac process was licensed exclusively to Halliburton.
[src:boilover/amoco] By the early 1950s, Standard Oil of Indiana was ranked as the second-largest American oil company with annual gross sales of $1.5 billion.
[src:boilover/amoco] It had 12 refineries in the United States, marketed its products in 41 states, owned 12,000 miles (19,000 km) of crude oil pipelines, 10,000 miles (16,000 km) of trunk lines, and 1,700 miles (2,700 km) of product pipelines.
[src:boilover/amoco] In October 1954, Standard Indiana opened its Mandan refinery in North Dakota under its American Oil Company subsidiary.
[src:boilover/amoco] In the late 1950s and early 1960s, Indiana Standard began to diversify its assets.
[src:boilover/amoco] It again led the way with scientific and technological discoveries.
[src:boilover/amoco] Indiana Standard discovered PTA, a chemical for polyester fiber production.
[src:boilover/amoco] In 1968, following that discovery, Indiana Standard acquired the Avisun Corporation and Patchogue-Plymouth, forming the Amoco Fabrics and Fibers Company.
[src:boilover/amoco] By 1992, the company was trying to sell off its yarn factories in Alabama and Georgia.
[src:boilover/amoco] The company's Amoco Foam Products subsidiary made polystyrene cups, plates, carrying trays and other products.
[src:boilover/amoco] The division was sold to Tenneco in June 1996.
[src:boilover/amoco] In 1956, the Pan-Am stations in the southeastern U.S. were rebranded as Amoco stations.
[src:boilover/amoco] Both brands shared the same redesigned torch and oval logo for easy identification nationwide.
[src:boilover/amoco] The Utoco (Utah Oil Company) name used in Indiana Standard's southwestern region was replaced by the American name.
[src:boilover/amoco] The Amoco name continued to be used outside the U.S. and as a brand on certain American Oil products.
[src:boilover/amoco] Soon after, the company began to expand.
[src:boilover/amoco] With an exploration office in Canada, Indiana Standard was now an international gas company.
[src:boilover/amoco] Indiana Standard created several new plants and claimed various new oil fields in this time period, as the company prospered in the post-war boom.
[src:boilover/amoco] By 1971, all the divisions of Indiana Standard bore the Amoco name including American Oil which was renamed Amoco Oil with American stations renamed Amoco stations.
[src:boilover/amoco] By 1975, Amoco began phasing in the Amoco name in the old Indiana Standard sales territory.
[src:boilover/amoco] Standard Oil Company (Indiana) was officially renamed Amoco Corporation in 1985.
[src:boilover/amoco] Facilities, like the one in Casper, were renamed using the new branding.
[src:boilover/amoco] Phillips Petroleum's assets in the General American Oil Company, acquired in 1983, were later taken over by Amoco.
[src:boilover/amoco] Carlin's Amoco Station was built at Roanoke, Virginia, around 1947; it was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 2012.
[src:boilover/amoco] Standard of Indiana established operations in Venezuela during the 1920s under dictator Juan Vicente Gomez.
[src:boilover/amoco] However, by 1932, during the worst of the Great Depression, the company sold its interests to Standard Oil of New Jersey.
[src:boilover/amoco] In 1958, Indiana again went overseas by signing a deal with Iran to develop oil interests in the Middle Eastern country, this marked the company's first expansion into the Middle East.
[src:boilover/amoco] However, during the 1978 Iranian Revolution, Indiana faced significant challenges as political unrest escalated.
[src:boilover/amoco] The company swiftly shut down its Iranian operations and evacuated all American employees after they received death threats.
[src:boilover/amoco] This marked Amoco's complete withdrawal from Iran.
[src:boilover/amoco] In addition, the company also acquired a division of Tenneco Oil Company and Dome Petroleum Limited becoming one of the world's largest oil companies.
[src:boilover/amoco] In April 1981, reorganized Amoco Production, Amoco Oil, Amoco Chemicals, and Amoco Minerals—its four main units—into worldwide operating concerns.
[src:boilover/amoco] The Amoco International Oil Company was also merged into Amoco Production, with its refining and marketing operations transferred to Amoco Oil and its marine transportation operations made part of Indiana Standard's supply and technology department.
[src:boilover/amoco] In July 1988, Amoco acquired Dome Petroleum, a Canadian company.
[src:boilover/amoco] By 1989, Amoco was the fifth-largest gasoline seller in the United States with more than 14,000 stations in 30 states.
[src:boilover/amoco] In 1994 Amoco was involved in a consortium with nine other companies that signed an agreement with the government of Azerbaijan for exclusive rights to develop oil fields in the Caspian Sea.
[src:boilover/amoco] Also in 1994 Amoco combined with competitors Shell Oil and Exxon to construct a $1 billion offshore oil platform in the Gulf of Mexico, the deepest in the world at the time.
[src:boilover/amoco] By the end of the 1990s, worldwide oil prices had slumped to their lowest point in over a decade.
[src:boilover/amoco] Amoco, the fourth largest US oil producer at the time, reported a 50% fall in earnings in second quarter of 1998.
[src:boilover/amoco] Analysts believed Amoco was hurt by its lack of international refining.
[src:boilover/amoco] On August 11, 1998, Amoco announced it would merge with BP in the world's largest industrial merger.
[src:boilover/amoco] Though billed as a merger of equals, BP held control of the new entity.
[src:boilover/amoco] Shareholder control was split 60/40 in favor of BP shareholders.
[src:boilover/amoco] The new company was also based in London, where BP was based, with BP chief executive Sir John Browne running the company.
[src:boilover/amoco] BP chairman Peter Sutherland and Amoco chairman Larry Fuller served as co-chairs.
[src:boilover/amoco] The consolidated company would also cut 6,000 jobs worldwide.
[src:boilover/amoco] The new company made efforts to further consolidate by announcing the acquisition of Atlantic Richfield Company (ARCO) for $26.8 billion in April 1999.
[src:boilover/amoco] However, it wasn't until BP Amoco agreed to divest ARCO's Alaska holdings that the FTC approved the deal a year later.
[src:boilover/amoco] In August 1999, BP Amoco sold its western Canadian oil properties for $1.1 billion, to Canadian Natural Resources ($690 million) and Penn West Petroleum ($410 million).
[src:boilover/amoco] In September 2001, BP Amoco sold its refineries in Salt Lake City and Mandan, North Dakota to Tesoro Petroleum.
[src:boilover/amoco] Originally, the plan was for all US BP service stations to be converted to Amoco while all overseas Amoco service stations were to be converted to BP.
[src:boilover/amoco] But by 2004, BP announced that all Amoco service stations would either be closed or renamed to BP service stations, including the remaining stations still bearing the "Standard" name.
[src:boilover/amoco] BP also chose to rename its gasolines with the Amoco name, changing its midgrade and premium offerings to the Silver and Ultimate brandings that Amoco used.
[src:boilover/amoco] By 2008, the "Amoco Fuels" name had been mostly discontinued in favor of "BP Gasoline with Invigorate".
[src:boilover/amoco] The Amoco name, however, lives on as BP continues to sell Silver and Ultimate under the BP name.
[src:boilover/amoco] In addition, a few BP stations continued operation under the Amoco name.
[src:boilover/amoco] Most were either converted to BP, demolished and replaced with BP-style stations, abandoned, or switched to competitor brands.
[src:boilover/amoco] On April 1, 2010, in Mississippi, Chevron purchased some BP gas stations, which had been Amoco, to convert them to the Texaco brand.
[src:boilover/amoco] In the aftermath of the *Deepwater Horizon* oil spill in the Gulf of Mexico, there were reports in the press that BP was reconsidering rebranding itself as Amoco in the US.
[src:boilover/amoco] Some independently owned BP stations, including former Amoco stations, switched to a different brand due to the public relations fallout as a result of the oil spill.
[src:boilover/amoco] The first Indiana Standard logo was unveiled in 1926, after a competition.
[src:boilover/amoco] The logo featured a circle, representing strength, stability, and dependability, with the words "Standard Oil Company (Indiana)" in red.
[src:boilover/amoco] The inner circle represents the cycle of service to customers.
[src:boilover/amoco] The word *Service* was written in the inside of the circles.
[src:boilover/amoco] In addition, the logo also had a torch with a flame, symbolizing progress.
[src:boilover/amoco] This logo appeared on gas station buildings.
[src:boilover/amoco] The roadside sign was a blue rectangle saying "STANDARD SERVICE" in white block letters.
[src:boilover/amoco] Concurrently, American Oil introduced in 1932, a logo which was the first to bear the name "Amoco".
[src:boilover/amoco] It featured an ellipse divided into three sections horizontally; the top and bottom were red, and the middle had a black background with white lettering.
[src:boilover/amoco] This logo was used in the northeastern U.S.
[src:boilover/amoco] A new logo was developed by Indiana Standard and introduced in 1946.
[src:boilover/amoco] It combined the Standard torch with the Amoco oval.
[src:boilover/amoco] The oval colors were, from top to bottom, red, white, and blue.
[src:boilover/amoco] The new logo was called the "Torch and Oval (T&O)".
[src:boilover/amoco] In parts of the country where the company could not use the name "Standard", the logo read "Utoco" (Utah Oil Company) or "Pan-Am".
[src:boilover/amoco] When the "Pan-Am" name was replaced by "Amoco", it marked the first time the torch and oval was used with the Amoco name.
[src:boilover/amoco] The red and black logo continued to be used in the northeast and maps distributed by Amoco in the late 1950s through 1960 showed both logos.
[src:boilover/amoco] In 1961, the torch and oval was redesigned with a flatter oval and a more contemporary torch design with the logo bearing the Standard or American name in the U.S. and the Amoco name outside the U.S.
[src:boilover/amoco] The next updated logo, in 1971, enhanced the previous one.
[src:boilover/amoco] It featured a blue bottom and a sleeker-looking torch.
[src:boilover/amoco] In addition, the word "Standard" became italicized and thicker.
[src:boilover/amoco] This was used by Midwestern station owners who had the option of using the Amoco name (more familiar in the East and South) or using the more familiar Standard name.
[src:boilover/amoco] Owners used it until they were converted to BP or another franchise.
[src:boilover/amoco] In the 1970s, both the Standard and Amoco brand icons were used on products (such as Amoco Roadmaps, Amoco Motorclub, and the Amaco Credit Card).
[src:boilover/amoco] The final Amoco logo of the company simply changed the name on the logo to "Amoco".
[src:boilover/amoco] The logo featured the familiar torch and divided ellipse.
[src:boilover/amoco] A horizontal logo was also used, with the italicized word "Amoco" featuring trailing red, white, and blue horizontal stripes, taken from the divided ellipse of the Amoco logo.
[src:boilover/amoco] This logo was used primarily on pumps and service station canopies.
[src:boilover/amoco] After the rebrand, for a time the Amoco brand was retained as a sub-brand to the main BP helios logo, mainly in the form of the horizontal logo (used on signage as a smaller element beneath the price displays); the black background was replaced with green, to symbolize the new parent company.
[src:boilover/amoco] Although a few Amoco stations still use their former logo, most have since been converted to the BP livery.
[src:boilover/amoco] Louis, Missouri, the largest Amoco sign in the world, both before and after the company's demise, still stands.
[src:boilover/amoco] It stands at the intersection of Clayton Road, Skinker Boulevard, McCausland Avenue, and Interstate 64 (near the southwest corner of Forest Park, home of the St.
[src:boilover/amoco] Louis Zoo, the Saint Louis Art Museum and other prominent attractions).
[src:boilover/amoco] It is visible up to two miles away on the interstate.
[src:boilover/amoco] Most surviving Amoco stations are kept so BP can continue holding the trademarks for Amoco and Standard.
[src:boilover/amoco] In May 2008, United States BP stations mostly discontinued use of the "Amoco Fuels" logo as BP introduced its new brand of fuel, "BP Gasoline with Invigorate".
[src:boilover/amoco] BP still uses the Silver and Amoco Ultimate brands for its midgrade and premium gasolines.
[src:boilover/amoco] For the 2017 revival (see below), the Amoco logo got a new, modernized refresh to its "torch and oval" image.
[src:boilover/amoco] In 1968–1972, (as American Oil Company) the company sponsored the American Freeway Patrol (AFP) in the metropolitan San Diego area as part of an expansion of service stations into Southern California.
[src:boilover/amoco] The American Freeway Patrol cruised the freeways and assisted disabled motorists free of charge, and provided helicopter traffic reports for local radio stations which was groundbreaking at the time.
[src:boilover/amoco] Don Langford, with KFWB (AM) Los Angeles, joined the American Freeway Patrol, San Diego, as traffic reporter on KOGO-AM-FM, KSON (AM), KITT (FM) San Diego, and KMLO (AM) Vista.
[src:boilover/amoco] In 1976, Amoco (under the "*Standard*" name) sponsored the Barney Oldfield Speedway attraction at Marriott's Great America theme park in Gurnee, Illinois.
[src:boilover/amoco] Although the sponsorship deal ended when Marriott sold the park to Six Flags in 1985, the *Standard* logo can still be seen on all of the Barney Oldfield Speedway (now Great America Raceway) cars.
[src:boilover/amoco] In 1988, legendary racer Mario Andretti drove the Amoco Ultimate Lola/Chevrolet for Newman/Haas Racing in the Indianapolis 500 and throughout the season in the CART IndyCar World Series.
[src:boilover/amoco] Andretti provided great publicity for Amoco by winning races at Phoenix and Cleveland that year, part of his 52 career IndyCar wins.
[src:boilover/amoco] Andretti also appeared in Amoco television commercials that aired in local race markets as part of the IndyCar sponsorship campaign.
[src:boilover/amoco] Dave Blaney drove a #93 Pontiac Grand Prix/Dodge Intrepid under Amoco sponsorship in the NASCAR Winston Cup Series and NASCAR Busch Series from 1997 until the brand's demise in 2001.
[src:boilover/amoco] On August 27, 1955, the Whiting refinery suffered a devastating fire when a processing tower exploded.
[src:boilover/amoco] The fire lasted eight days, consumed 45 acres of storage tanks, and damaged nearby homes and businesses.
[src:boilover/amoco] In all, two people were killed, another 40 were injured, and 1,500 were evacuated.
[src:boilover/amoco] By the following year, the facility was repaired and the company had purchased much of the surrounding area in order to expand.
[src:boilover/amoco] In November 1978, abnormally high temperatures were detected in fuel tanks in the basement of an Amoco gas station in Centralia, Pennsylvania, owned by then-mayor John Coddington.
[src:boilover/amoco] The source was determined to be the town's ongoing mine fire.
[src:boilover/amoco] To prevent risk of the fuel igniting, the gasoline in the tanks was drained.
[src:boilover/amoco] The gas station was shuttered in December 1979, and demolished on November 9, 1981.
[src:boilover/amoco] On March 16, 1978, the very large crude carrier *Amoco Cadiz* ran ashore just north of Landunvez, Finistère, Brittany, France, causing one of the largest oil spills in history.
[src:boilover/amoco] Amoco was ordered by a federal judge Charles Norgle in a 1990 ruling to pay $120 million in damages and restitution to France.
[src:boilover/amoco] On October 21, 1980, an explosion at an Amoco plant in New Castle, Delaware, killed six people, caused $46 million in property damage, and eventually led to the loss of 300 jobs.
[src:boilover/amoco] In the 1980s and 1990s, six former Amoco chemical engineers at the firm's Naperville, Illinois, research campus developed a deadly form of brain cancer.
[src:boilover/amoco] Researchers who conducted a three-year study of the cancer cluster determined that the cancer cases were workplace-related, but they could not identify the source of the workers' ailments.
[src:boilover/amoco] In June 2010, BP demolished Building 503, where the employees had worked.
[src:boilover/amoco] According to a company spokesperson, the building was "underused", and "required upgrades the company deemed too expensive".
[src:boilover/amoco] Heirs of one of the cancer-stricken workers won a $2.75 million suit against BP Amoco in 2000.
[src:boilover/amoco] It was announced on October 10, 2017, that BP would bring the Amoco name back, after an absence of almost a decade.
[src:boilover/amoco] BP had said the first station would relaunch in 2017.
[src:boilover/amoco] Its intention for relaunching the name was to capture more of the U.S. fuel industry.
[src:boilover/amoco] As such, aside from the aforementioned St.
[src:boilover/amoco] Louis station with the large Amoco sign as well as a few other isolated instances, most newer Amoco stations were converted from competitor brands as opposed to BP.
[src:boilover/amoco] Several Gulf stations were rechristened as Amoco stations on Long Island, New York, starting in November 2017.
[src:boilover/amoco] The Amoco brand returned to the Pittsburgh market in fall 2020, when locally based Coen Markets announced a marketing deal with BP to sell Amoco-branded gasoline at all of its fuel-offering locations.
[src:boilover/amoco] As most of Coen's stores were already selling BP gasoline (with a small handful having been Amoco stations before BP), this marked the largest switchover from BP to Amoco since the brand's reintroduction, though a few Coen stations were also selling Exxon, Sunoco, and Citgo prior to the deal.
[src:boilover/amoco] While the deal didn't affect BP as a whole, as BP lost several stations in the market to Marathon Petroleum years before, it essentially relegated the BP brand to 7-Eleven stations in the market as well as a few independent operators.
[src:boilover/amoco] Following the acquisition of TravelCenters of America in May 2023, BP began converting all pumps to either BP or Amoco branding.
[src:boilover/amoco] In February 2024, there were 675 Amoco gas stations in the United States.
[src:boilover/amoco] In May 2025, Amoco has 900 stations across the United States.
[src:boilover/area-of-refuge] An **area of refuge** or **safe room** is a place in a building designed to hold occupants during a fire or other emergency when evacuation may not be safe or possible.
[src:boilover/area-of-refuge] Occupants can wait there until rescued or relieved by firefighters.
[src:boilover/area-of-refuge] In some instances, an area of refuge or refuge area may refer to a designated space in a multi-unit residential building that can provide relief from unsafe or uncomfortable conditions in individual units.
[src:boilover/area-of-refuge] An area of refuge is typically supplied with a steady supply of fresh or filtered outside air.
[src:boilover/area-of-refuge] A two way communication system is provided on each floor above or below the main floor.
[src:boilover/area-of-refuge] A call box is required in each area of refuge, which can call into a central location called a base station.
[src:boilover/area-of-refuge] If the station is not attended 24 hours a day, the call must automatically call to an outside location and have two-way voice person to person communication capabilities.
[src:boilover/area-of-refuge] Such locations are usually required to be bounded by fire-resistant walls and floors.
[src:boilover/area-of-refuge] In the context of climate change, where older buildings may not be designed for changing climate conditions, refuge spaces are sometimes discussed in terms of providing communal areas in multi-unit buildings for when temperature and air quality is not safe or comfortable in individual units.
[src:boilover/arthur-b-guise-medal] Guise Medal** was established in 1983 and has been awarded annually starting in 1985 by the Society of Fire Protection Engineers.
[src:boilover/arthur-b-guise-medal] Named in memory of Arthur Guise, an engineer who developed dry chemicals as fire extinguishing agents, it recognizes eminent achievement in the advancement of the science and technology of fire protection engineering.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] The American English terms *asphalt* (or *asphaltic*) *concrete*, *bituminous asphalt concrete*, and *bituminous mixture* are typically used only in engineering and construction documents, which define concrete as any composite material composed of mineral aggregate adhered with a binder.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] The abbreviation, *AC*, is sometimes used for *asphalt concrete* but can also denote *asphalt content* or *asphalt cement*, referring to the liquid asphalt portion of the composite material.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] The Procession Street of Babylonian King Nabopolassar, c.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] 625 BC, leading north from his palace through the city's wall, was described as being constructed from burnt brick and asphalt.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Natural asphalt covered and bonded cobblestones were used from 1824 in France as a means to construct roads, as were moulded asphalt cobbles or blocks, formed from rammed natural rock asphalt.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] In 1829 natural Seyssel asphalt mixed with 7% aggregate, to create an asphat-mastic surface, was used for a footpath at Pont Morand, Lyon, France, the technique spreading to Paris in 1835, London, England, in 1836, and Philadelphia, United States, in 1838.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Claridge obtained a similar English patent (GB patent 1837 #7849), substituting Seyssel asphalt as the binder, having seen it employed in France and Belgium; he would subsequently form the Claridge's Patent Asphalte Company, in 1838.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] A 2-mile (3.2 km) stretch of a gravel constructed road, running out of Nottingham, was experimentally covered in natural asphalt in 1840.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] This experiment was repeated in 1845 in Huntingdon High Street.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] A macadam road surfaced with asphalt was constructed in 1852, between Paris and Perpignan, France, using Swiss Val de Travers rock asphalt (natural asphalt-covered limestone aggregate).
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] In 1869, Threadneedle Street, in London, was resurfaced with Swiss Val de Travers rock asphalt.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] He filed a UK patent, in 1902, for his improvement.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Hooley founding a UK company to market the technology, where the term *tar macadam*, shortened to *tarmac*, was coined, after the name of his company *Tar Macadam (Purnell Hooley's Patent) Syndicate Limited*, derived from the combination of tar and macadam gravel composite mixtures.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] and drying the aggregate to remove moisture from it prior to mixing.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Paving and compaction must be performed while the asphalt is sufficiently hot.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] In many locales paving is restricted to summer months because in winter the base will cool the asphalt too quickly before it can be packed to the required density.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] It is also used as an environmental liner for landfills, reservoirs, and fish hatchery ponds.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] or sometimes water to the asphalt binder prior to mixing.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] This improves working conditions, and lowers laying-temperature, which leads to more rapid availability of the surface for use, which is important for construction sites with critical time schedules.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] The usage of these additives in hot-mixed asphalt (above) may afford easier compaction and allow cold-weather paving or longer hauls.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] A survey of US asphalt producers found that nearly 25% of asphalt produced in 2012 was warm mix, a 416% increase since 2009.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Cleaner road pavements can be potentially developed by combining WMA and material recycling.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Warm Mix Asphalt (WMA) technology has environmental, production, and economic benefits.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] While in its emulsified state, the bitumen is less viscous and the mixture is easy to work and compact.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] The emulsion will break after enough water evaporates and the cold mix will, ideally, take on the properties of an HMA pavement.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Cold mix is commonly used as a patching material and on lesser-trafficked service roads.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] While in its dissolved state, the bitumen is less viscous and the mix is easy to work and compact.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] After the mix is laid down the lighter fraction evaporates.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] in the lighter fraction, cut-back asphalt has been largely replaced by asphalt emulsion.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] This is produced by heating hard grade blown bitumen (i.e., partly oxidised) in a green cooker (mixer) until it has become a viscous liquid after which the aggregate mix is then added.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] The bitumen aggregate mixture is cooked (matured) for around 6–8 hours and once it is ready, the mastic asphalt mixer is transported to the work site where experienced layers empty the mixer and either machine or hand lay the mastic asphalt contents on to the road.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] while offering as very high fatigue strengths.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] High-modulus asphalt layers are used both in reinforcement operations and in the construction of new reinforcements for medium and heavy traffic.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] In base layers, they tend to exhibit a greater capacity of absorbing tensions and, in general, better fatigue resistance.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] In addition to the asphalt and aggregate, additives, such as polymers, and antistripping agents may be added to improve the properties of the final product.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Areas paved with asphalt concrete—especially airport aprons—have been called "the tarmac" at times, despite not being constructed using the tarmacadam process.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] A variety of specialty asphalt concrete mixtures have been developed to meet specific needs, such as stone-matrix asphalt, which is designed to ensure a strong wearing surface, or porous asphalt pavements, which are permeable and allow water to drain through the pavement for controlling storm water.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Different types of asphalt concrete have different performance characteristics in roads in terms of surface durability, tire wear, braking efficiency and roadway noise.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] In principle, the determination of appropriate asphalt performance characteristics must take into account the volume of traffic in each vehicle category, and the performance requirements of the friction course.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] In general, the viscosity of asphalt allows it to conveniently form a convex surface, and a central apex to streets and roads to drain water to the edges.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] This is not, however, in itself an advantage over concrete, which has various grades of viscosity and can be formed into a convex road surface.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Rather, it is the economy of asphalt concrete that renders it more frequently used.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Concrete is found on interstate highways where maintenance is highly crucial.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Asphalt concrete generates less roadway noise than a Portland cement concrete surface, and is typically less noisy than chip seal surfaces.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Because tire noise is generated through the conversion of kinetic energy to sound waves, more noise is produced as the speed of a vehicle increases.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] The notion that highway design might take into account acoustical engineering considerations, including the selection of the type of surface paving, arose in the early 1970s.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] With regard to structural performance, the asphalt behaviour depends on a variety of factors including the material, loading and environmental condition.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Furthermore, the performance of pavement varies over time.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Therefore, the long-term behaviour of asphalt pavement is different from its short-term performance.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] The LTPP is a research program by the FHWA, which is specifically focusing on long-term pavement behaviour.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Asphalt deterioration can include crocodile cracking, potholes, upheaval, raveling, bleeding, rutting, shoving, stripping, and grade depressions.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] In cold climates, frost heaves can crack asphalt even in one winter.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Filling the cracks with bitumen is a temporary fix, but only proper compaction and drainage can slow this process.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Factors that cause asphalt concrete to deteriorate over time mostly fall into one of three categories: construction quality, environmental considerations, and traffic loads.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Often, damage results from combinations of factors in all three categories.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Construction quality is critical to pavement performance.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] This includes the construction of utility trenches and appurtenances that are placed in the pavement after construction.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Lack of compaction in the surface of the asphalt, especially on the longitudinal joint, can reduce the life of a pavement by 30 to 40%.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Service trenches in pavements after construction have been said to reduce the life of the pavement by 50%, mainly due to the lack of compaction in the trench, and because of water intrusion through improperly sealed joints.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Environmental factors include heat and cold, the presence of water in the subbase or subgrade soil underlying the pavement, and frost heaves.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] High temperatures soften the asphalt binder, allowing heavy tire loads to deform the pavement into ruts.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Paradoxically, high heat and strong sunlight also cause the asphalt to oxidize, becoming stiffer and less resilient, leading to crack formation.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Cold temperatures can cause cracks as the asphalt contracts.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Cold asphalt is also less resilient and more vulnerable to cracking.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Water trapped under the pavement softens the subbase and subgrade, making the road more vulnerable to traffic loads.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Water under the road freezes and expands in cold weather, causing and enlarging cracks.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] In spring thaw, the ground thaws from the top down, so water is trapped between the pavement above and the still-frozen soil underneath.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] This layer of saturated soil provides little support for the road above, leading to the formation of potholes.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] This is more of a problem for silty or clay soils than sandy or gravelly soils.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Some jurisdictions pass frost laws to reduce the allowable weight of trucks during the spring thaw season and protect their roads.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] The damage a vehicle causes is roughly proportional to the axle load raised to the fourth power, so doubling the weight an axle carries actually causes 16 times as much damage.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Wheels cause the road to flex slightly, resulting in fatigue cracking, which often leads to crocodile cracking.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Slowly moving vehicles stress the road over a longer period of time, increasing ruts, cracking, and corrugations in the asphalt pavement.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Other causes of damage include heat damage from vehicle fires, or solvent action from chemical spills.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] The life of a road can be prolonged through good design, construction and maintenance practices.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] During design, engineers measure the traffic on a road, paying special attention to the number and types of trucks.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] They also evaluate the subsoil to see how much load it can withstand.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] The pavement and subbase thicknesses are designed to withstand the wheel loads.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Sometimes, geogrids are used to reinforce the subbase and further strengthen the roads.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Drainage, including ditches, storm drains and underdrains are used to remove water from the roadbed, preventing it from weakening the subbase and subsoil.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Sealcoating asphalt is a maintenance measure that helps keep water and petroleum products out of the pavement.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Maintaining and cleaning ditches and storm drains will extend the life of the road at low cost.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Sealing small cracks with bituminous crack sealer prevents water from enlarging cracks through frost weathering, or percolating down to the subbase and softening it.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] For somewhat more distressed roads, a chip seal or similar surface treatment may be applied.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] As the number, width and length of cracks increases, more intensive repairs are needed.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] In order of generally increasing expense, these include thin asphalt overlays, multicourse overlays, grinding off the top course and overlaying, in-place recycling, or full-depth reconstruction of the roadway.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] It is far less expensive to keep a road in good condition than it is to repair it once it has deteriorated.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] This is why some agencies place the priority on preventive maintenance of roads in good condition, rather than reconstructing roads in poor condition.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Poor roads are upgraded as resources and budget allow.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] In terms of lifetime cost and long term pavement conditions, this will result in better system performance.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Agencies that concentrate on restoring their bad roads often find that by the time they have repaired them all, the roads that were in good condition have deteriorated.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Some agencies use a pavement management system to help prioritize maintenance and repairs.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Asphalt concrete is a recyclable material that can be reclaimed and reused both on-site and in asphalt plants.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] The most common recycled component in asphalt concrete is reclaimed asphalt pavement (RAP).
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] RAP is recycled at a greater rate than any other material in the United States.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Many roofing shingles also contain asphalt, and asphalt concrete mixes may contain reclaimed asphalt shingles (RAS).
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Research has demonstrated that RAP and RAS can replace the need for up to 100% of the virgin aggregate and asphalt binder in a mix, but this percentage is typically lower due to regulatory requirements and performance concerns.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] In 2019, new asphalt pavement mixtures produced in the United States contained, on average, 21.1% RAP and 0.2% RAS.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Recycled asphalt components may be reclaimed and transported to an asphalt plant for processing and use in new pavements, or the entire recycling process may be conducted in-place.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] While in-place recycling typically occurs on roadways and is specific to RAP, recycling in asphalt plants may utilize RAP, RAS, or both.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] In 2019, an estimated 97.0 million tons of RAP and 1.1 million tons of RAS were accepted by asphalt plants in the United States.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] RAP is typically received by plants after being milled on-site, but pavements may also be ripped out in larger sections and crushed in the plant.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] RAP millings are typically stockpiled at plants before being incorporated into new asphalt mixes.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Prior to mixing, stockpiled millings may be dried and any that have agglomerated in storage may have to be crushed.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] RAS may be received by asphalt plants as post-manufacturer waste directly from shingle factories, or they may be received as post-consumer waste at the end of their service life.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Processing of RAS includes grinding the shingles and sieving the grinds to remove oversized particles.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] The grinds may also be screened with a magnetic sieve to remove nails and other metal debris.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] The ground RAS is then dried, and the asphalt cement binder can be extracted.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] For further information on RAS processing, performance, and associated health and safety concerns, see Asphalt Shingles.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] In-place recycling methods allow roadways to be rehabilitated by reclaiming the existing pavement, remixing, and repaving on-site.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] In-place recycling techniques include rubblizing, hot in-place recycling, cold in-place recycling, and full-depth reclamation.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] For further information on in-place methods, see Road Surface.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] During its service life, the asphalt cement binder, which makes up about 5–6% of a typical asphalt concrete mix, naturally hardens and becomes stiffer.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] This aging process primarily occurs due to oxidation, evaporation, exudation, and physical hardening.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] For this reason, asphalt mixes containing RAP and RAS are prone to exhibiting lower workability and increased susceptibility to fatigue cracking.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] These issues are avoidable if the recycled components are apportioned correctly in the mix.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Practicing proper storage and handling, such as by keeping RAP stockpiles out of damp areas or direct sunlight, is also important in avoiding quality issues.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] The binder aging process may also produce some beneficial attributes, such as by contributing to higher levels of rutting resistance in asphalts containing RAP and RAS.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] One approach to balancing the performance aspects of RAP and RAS is to combine the recycled components with virgin aggregate and virgin asphalt binder.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] This approach can be effective when the recycled content in the mix is relatively low, and has a tendency to work more effectively with soft virgin binders.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] A 2020 study found that the addition of 5% RAS to a mix with a soft, low-grade virgin binder significantly increased the mix's rutting resistance while maintaining adequate fatigue cracking resistance.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] In mixes with higher recycled content, the addition of virgin binder becomes less effective, and rejuvenators may be used.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Rejuvenators are additives that restore the physical and chemical properties of the aged binder.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] When conventional mixing methods are used in asphalt plants, the upper limit for RAP content before rejuvenators become necessary has been estimated at 50%.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Research has demonstrated that the use of rejuvenators at optimal doses can allow for mixes with 100% recycled components to meet the performance requirements of conventional asphalt concrete.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Beyond RAP and RAS, a range of waste materials can be re-used in place of virgin aggregate, or as rejuvenators.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Crumb rubber, generated from recycled tires, has been demonstrated to improve the fatigue resistance and flexural strength of asphalt mixes that contain RAP.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] In California, legislative mandates require the Department of Transportation to incorporate crumb rubber into asphalt paving materials.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Other recycled materials that are actively included in asphalt concrete mixes across the United States include steel slag, blast furnace slag, and cellulose fibers.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Further research has been conducted to discover new forms of waste that may be recycled into asphalt mixes.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] A 2020 study conducted in Melbourne, Australia presented a range of strategies for incorporating waste materials into asphalt concrete.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] The strategies presented in the study include the use of plastics, particularly high-density polyethylene, in asphalt binders, and the use of glass, brick, ceramic, and marble quarry waste in place of traditional aggregate.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Rejuvenators may also be produced from recycled materials, including waste engine oil, waste vegetable oil, and waste vegetable grease.
[src:boilover/asphalt-concrete] Recently, discarded face masks have been incorporated into stone mastic.
[src:boilover/aspirating-smoke-detector] An **aspirating smoke detector** (**ASD**) is a system used in active fire protection, consisting of a central detection unit which draws air through a network of pipes to detect smoke.
[src:boilover/aspirating-smoke-detector] The sampling chamber is based on a nephelometer that detects the presence of smoke particles suspended in air by detecting the light scattered by them in the chamber.
[src:boilover/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASDs can typically detect smoke before it is visible to the naked eye.
[src:boilover/aspirating-smoke-detector] In most cases aspirating smoke detectors require a fan unit to draw in a sample of air from the protected area through its network of pipes.
[src:boilover/aspirating-smoke-detector] In 1970 the Australian Commonwealth Scientific and Industrial Research Organisation (CSIRO) used a nephelometer to carry out research into forest fires.
[src:boilover/aspirating-smoke-detector] Subsequently, the Australian Postmaster-General's Department engaged the CSIRO to investigate technologies that could prevent service interruption due to fire.
[src:boilover/aspirating-smoke-detector] After selecting a sample site to carry out research, the CSIRO suggested that the nephelometer should be used as the benchmark for the APO fire tests.
[src:boilover/aspirating-smoke-detector] This was installed to monitor smoke levels within the return-air ducts of the mechanical ventilation system, utilising a chart-recorder output display.
[src:boilover/aspirating-smoke-detector] At the conclusion of several weeks of testing, it was discovered that there no commercially available fire detection technology suitable for preventing damage to telephone equipment.
[src:boilover/aspirating-smoke-detector] One technology that did show great promise however was the nephelometer itself.
[src:boilover/aspirating-smoke-detector] In 1979, Xtralis, then IEI Pty Ltd., produced and sold an air sampling device they called VESDA (Very Early Smoke Detection Apparatus).
[src:boilover/aspirating-smoke-detector] The company redesigned the detector in 1982 to provide the reliability, features, size and reduced cost for export markets.
[src:boilover/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD systems have gained popularity due to their ability to sense smoke long before a catastrophic incident.
[src:boilover/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD design corrects shortcomings of conventional smoke detectors by using a sampling pipe with multiple holes.
[src:boilover/aspirating-smoke-detector] The air samples are captured and filtered, removing any contaminants or dust to avoid false alarms and then processed by a centralized, highly sensitive laser detection unit.
[src:boilover/aspirating-smoke-detector] If smoke is detected, the systems alarm is triggered, and signals are then processed through centralized monitoring stations within a few seconds.
[src:boilover/aspirating-smoke-detector] Unlike passive smoke detection systems, including spot detectors, ASD systems actively draw smoke to the detector through bore holes within a piping system that runs throughout the protected area.
[src:boilover/aspirating-smoke-detector] Furthermore, ASD systems incorporate integrity monitoring to ensure an alert is raised at any time the ASD's ability to detect smoke is compromised.
[src:boilover/aspirating-smoke-detector] This is not the case with passive devices that are generally only electrically monitored with no ability to determine if smoke can actually reach the detection element.
[src:boilover/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD systems incorporate more than one level of alarm.
[src:boilover/aspirating-smoke-detector] This allows an ASD system to provide very early warning of an event, prompting investigation at the earliest smouldering stage of a fire when it is easily addressed.
[src:boilover/aspirating-smoke-detector] Other alarm levels may be configured to provide fire alarm inputs to fire systems as well as releasing suppression systems.
[src:boilover/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD alarm sensitivities are configurable and can be programmed to levels ranging from thousands of times more sensitive than a conventional detector, to much less sensitive.
[src:boilover/aspirating-smoke-detector] The detectors work best in non-volatile environments.
[src:boilover/aspirating-smoke-detector] They can also be used in computer cabinets to alert users to the overheating of computer cables or individual computer components.
[src:boilover/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASDs are suitable for environments where a highly sensitive rapid smoke detection capability is required.
[src:boilover/aspirating-smoke-detector] This makes them suitable in clean rooms; areas which contain goods easily damaged by fire, such as tobacco, electronic rooms and highly flammable liquid and gases.
[src:boilover/aspirating-smoke-detector] Often, normal point detectors will recognise the danger too late, as smoke often does not reach the ceiling quickly enough for a fire to be detected in a timely fashion.
[src:boilover/aspirating-smoke-detector] As they can be easily hidden, pipe networks are suitable in environments where point detectors can be considered aesthetically displeasing, such as offices, apartments and hotel rooms.
[src:boilover/aspirating-smoke-detector] This factor also makes them suitable in locations where point detectors can be easily tampered with, such as in correctional facilities.
[src:boilover/aspirating-smoke-detector] Despite their high sensitivity ASDs can be used in dusty or dirty environments as long as correct design, installation and maintenance processes are followed.
[src:boilover/aspirating-smoke-detector] Most ASD products can accommodate a broad range of environments and applications – from both confined and open spaces to the cleanest or dirtiest environment, including telecomm, control rooms, waste treatment, mining and more.
[src:boilover/boilover] A **boilover** (or **boil-over**) is an extremely hazardous phenomenon in which a layer of water under a pool fire (e.g., an open-top tank fire) starts boiling, which results in a significant increase in fire intensity accompanied by violent expulsion of burning fluid to the surrounding areas.
[src:boilover/boilover] Boilover can only occur if the liquid fluid is a mixture of different chemical species with sufficiently diverse boiling points, although a so-called *thin-layer* *boilover* – a far less hazardous phenomenon – can arise from any water-immiscible liquid fuel.
[src:boilover/boilover] Crude oil, kerosene and some diesel oils are examples of fuels giving rise to boilover.
[src:boilover/boilover] Boilovers at industrial scale are rare but can lead to serious plant damage.
[src:boilover/boilover] Given the sudden and not easily predictable onset of the phenomenon, fatalities can occur, especially among firefighters and bystanders that have not been made to leave the area.
[src:boilover/boilover] The extreme violence of boilovers is due to the expansion of water from liquid to steam, which is by a factor of 1500 or more.
[src:boilover/boilover] A typical scenario for a tank fire that may eventually result in boilover is an initial confined explosion blowing off the tank roof.
[src:boilover/boilover] Pure chemical species are not liable to boilover.
[src:boilover/boilover] In order for one to occur, the material must be a mixture of species with sufficiently diverse boiling points.
[src:boilover/boilover] Crude oil and some commercial hydrocarbon mixtures, such as kerosene and some diesel oils, are examples of such materials.
[src:boilover/boilover] The fact that these are stored in large atmospheric tanks in refineries, tank farms, power stations, etc. makes boilover a hazard of interest in terms of process safety.
[src:boilover/boilover] During a pool fire, a distillation process takes place in the fuel.
[src:boilover/boilover] Separation of light components from heavier ones occurs thanks to convective fluid motion.
[src:boilover/boilover] An intermediate fuel layer, called the *hot zone* or *heat wave*, is formed, which becomes progressively richer in higher-boiling-point species.
[src:boilover/boilover] Its temperature, as well as thickness, progressively increase.
[src:boilover/boilover] Its lower boundary moves downwards towards the fuel–water interface at a speed higher than the overall level of fuel decreases due to the fire burning it.
[src:boilover/boilover] As a result, when the hot zone reaches the water layer, a considerable amount of unburnt fuel may still be present above the water.
[src:boilover/boilover] Upon the water contacting the hot zone, some steam forms.
[src:boilover/boilover] The resulting turbulence promotes mixing of the water into the hot fuel.
[src:boilover/boilover] This can result in rapid water vaporization.
[src:boilover/boilover] The violent expansion of the steam bubbles will push out a significant part of the fuel above it, causing a violent overflow of flaming liquid.
[src:boilover/boilover] In these conditions water may be superheated, in which case part of it goes through an explosive boiling with homogeneous nucleation of steam.
[src:boilover/boilover] When this happens, the abruptness of the expansion further enhances the expulsion of blazing fuel.
[src:boilover/boilover] Typical hot-zone speeds are 0.3–0.5 meters per hour (1.0–1.7 ft/h), although speeds of up to 1.2 meters per hour (4.0 ft/h) have been recorded.
[src:boilover/boilover] The hazards posed by a hot-zone boilover are significant for several reasons.
[src:boilover/boilover] At industrial scale, hydrocarbon tanks can contain up to hundreds of thousands of barrels of fluid.
[src:boilover/boilover] If a boilover occurs, the amount of blazing liquid erupting from the tank can therefore be huge.
[src:boilover/boilover] Ejected blazing fluids can travel at speeds up to 32 kilometres per hour (20 mph) and attain distances well in excess of the limits of secondary containment bunding, often hundreds of meters or in the order of ten tank diameters downwind.
[src:boilover/boilover] Bunding, however, remains an important measure to reduce fire spread.
[src:boilover/boilover] Moreover, since boilover inception is sometimes unpredictable —either in terms of time to onset or whether it will occur at all (because the presence of water in the tank bottom may not be a known factor)— the impact on the firefighters that have intervened to control the fire can be deadly.
[src:boilover/boilover] In some cases, simple bystanders were caught in the blaze and perished.
[src:boilover/boilover] Tank fires that appear to be relatively stable may burst into massive boilovers several hours after the fire starts, as it occurred in the Tacoa disaster.
[src:boilover/boilover] Failure to appreciate the hazards posed by a water layer underneath the fuel has been a significant contributing cause to the aftermath of boilover accidents, in terms of human and material losses.
[src:boilover/boilover] Uncertainty surrounding the time to boilover onset adds unpredictability that further complicates the efforts of the firefighting services.
[src:boilover/boilover] Mathematical models for boilover have been developed that predict the time necessary for boilover to initiate, among other things.
[src:boilover/boilover] In a thin-layer boilover, the size of the flames increases upon boilover onset, and a characteristic crackling sound is produced.
[src:boilover/boilover] However, due to the little amount of fuel left, this phenomenon is far less hazardous than a standard boilover.
[src:boilover/boilover] The study of thin-layer boilover is of interest in the context of *in-situ* burning of oil spills over water.
[src:boilover/boilover] A demonstration of chip pan fire slopover: Oil is heated and ignites, a small amount of water is poured on the fire and a violent plume of flames rises to the room ceiling.
[src:boilover/boilover] A *slopover* is a phenomenon similar to boilover, although distinct from it.
[src:boilover/boilover] It occurs when water is poured onto the fuel while a pool fire is occurring.
[src:boilover/boilover] If the fire is small enough, the water that instantly boils in contact with the fire or with the lower layers of blazing liquid (which are themselves not on fire but may be hotter than the water boiling point) can extend the flames, especially in the upwards direction.
[src:boilover/boilover] In industrial-scale tank fires, there is no noticeable effect when water is doused on the fire, although water sinking to the bottom of the tank may contribute to a later boilover.
[src:boilover/boilover] However, at smaller scale, slopovers pose significant hazards.
[src:boilover/boilover] Trying to extinguish a chip pan or cooking oil fire with water, for example, causes slopover, which can harm people and spread the fire in the kitchen.
[src:boilover/boilover] Serious burn incidents have also occurred during Mid-autumn Festival celebrations, where boiling candlewax and pouring water on it for entertainment has become a habit.
[src:boilover/boilover] A *frothover* occurs when a water layer is present under a layer of a viscous oil that is not on fire and whose temperature is higher than the water boiling point.
[src:boilover/boilover] An example is hot asphalt loaded into a tank car containing some water.
[src:boilover/boilover] Although nothing may happen at first, water may eventually superheat and later start to boil violently, resulting in overflow.
[src:boilover/boilover] Water is generally unsuitable for extinguishing liquid fires.
[src:boilover/boilover] In the context of boilovers and slopovers, the fuel is generally lighter than water.
[src:boilover/boilover] At industrial scale, this means that water applied to an open-top tank fire will sink to the bottom of the tank, which can cause boilover at a later stage.
[src:boilover/boilover] At small/domestic scale, assuming the water can find its way down through the fuel, use of water may cause the content of the vessel to spill over and spread the fire.
[src:boilover/boilover] If water does not sink efficiently to the bottom, then a violent slopover may occur.
[src:boilover/boilover] This makes water both inefficient as an extinguishing agent and potentially very hazardous.
[src:boilover/boilover] Hot-zone boilovers of large tanks are relatively rare events.
[src:boilover/boilover] However, they can be extremely disruptive.
[src:boilover/boilover] Therefore, prevention and control are very important.
[src:boilover/boilover] Boilover can be prevented by regularly checking for and draining water in the tank bottoms.
[src:boilover/boilover] In terms of plant layout, intertank distances would have to exceed five tank diameters in order to prevent escalation to adjacent tanks.
[src:boilover/boilover] In most cases, it is not feasible to design for such an arrangement.
[src:boilover/boilover] Open-top crude oil tank fires can be tackled using firefighting foam at rates of 10–12 L/(min × m2).
[src:boilover/boilover] However, it is not clear if these rates are adequate to minimize the potential for a boilover event, especially in cases where foam attack is initiated long after the inception of the tank fire.
[src:boilover/boilover] It has been suggested that foam firefighting should be started within 2–4 hours from ignition.
[src:boilover/boilover] Thermal radiation during a boilover is considerably higher than during the pool fire that precedes it.
[src:boilover/boilover] Although the event is short-lived, emergency response activities, for which tenable levels of thermal radiations are typically 6.3 kW/m2, cannot be safely accomplished, so operations should take place from a safe distance.
[src:boilover/boilover] Some approaches are available to assess the probability of and the proximity to boilover in tank fires.
[src:boilover/boilover] An estimation can be made *a priori* from the distillation curve and the properties of the fuel, with the aid of mathematical formulas, including the ones given above.
[src:boilover/boilover] However, this approach requires knowledge of the depth of the water layer at the bottom of the tank.
[src:boilover/boilover] Further, it does not consider the potential for a layer of water–fuel emulsion being present above the water.
[src:boilover/boilover] Progression of the hot zone can be monitored by using vertical strips of intumescent paint applied to the tank walls, or applying a water jet to the walls to assess at what height it starts boiling.
[src:boilover/boilover] Use of thermographic cameras or pyrometers has also been proposed.
[src:boilover/boilover] However, uncertainty regarding the presence and depth of a water or a water–fuel emulsion layer remains, and unpredictability about boilover onset cannot be completely dispelled.
[src:boilover/boilover] Draining the product from the tank may reduce accidental consequences, because less fluid would be subject to boilover.
[src:boilover/boilover] However, pumping out product may also reduce the time to boilover onset.
